ives by merely keeping a body alive. For the Inuit, and perhaps for all of us, life is "somewhere else," and the task is to articulate forms of care for others that are adequate to that truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aInuitxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistory. 0aInuitxMedical carezCanadaxHistory. 0aTuberculosiszCanadaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  acanadian history.  acanadian inuit.  acollection of stories.  aethnographer.  aethnography.  ahistorical biography.  amental health.  anew life.  aprofessor.  apsychologist.  areincarnation.  asociologist.  asomewhere else.  asuicide epidemic.  atuberculosis epidemic.  aunderstanding our world.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028260540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095855540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958555/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY